ive"]},{"pos":"verb","gloss":"to envelop, to enshroud, to cloak, to screen","tags":["transitive"]},{"pos":"verb","gloss":"to descend, to fall, to become night","tags":["transitive"],"examples":[{"text":"11 Century CE, Wallada bint al-Mustakfi, ترقب إذا جن الظلام زيارتي\nتَرَقَّبْ إِذَا جَنَّ الظَّلَامُ زِيَارَتِي / فَإِنِّي رَأَيْتُ اللَّيْلَ أَكْتَمَ لِلسِّرِّ\ntaraqqab ʔiḏā janna ẓ-ẓalāmu ziyāratī / fa-ʔinnī raʔaytu l-layla ʔaktama li-s-sirri","english":"Await, when darkness falls, my visit. For I found the night to be a better keeper of secrets."}]},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"spiritual or otherwise unseen, undetectable, masked, or morphed beings that may be benevolent or helpful (agathodaemons, eudaemons), neutral, or malevolent (cacodemons); demonkind, jinn, genies","tags":["collective"]},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"any mythical beings in general (such as fairies, satyrs, nymphs, elves, goblins, and sprites)","tags":["collective"]},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"a genie, a jann, one of the jinn(s).","tags":["collective","informal","singular"]},{"pos":"verb","gloss":"to be possessed; to seem or act as if possessed, to be insane, to be crazy, to be mad, to be deranged"},{"pos":"verb","gloss":"to be possessed; to be obsessed; to be infatuated"},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"verbal noun of جُنَّ (junna) (form I)","tags":["form-of","noun-from-verb"]},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"verbal noun of جَنَّ (janna) (form I)","tags":["form-of","noun-from-verb"]}]},"etymology":{"source":"wiktextract","text":"Compare Hebrew גָּנַן (gānán, “to defend, to cover”).\n\nFormally from the root ج ن ن (j n n), related to disappearance, hiding and concealment, though most likely a back-formation from جِنِّي (jinnī), derived from Classical Syriac ܓܢܝ (gnē, “spirit, genie”), or its emphatic form Aramaic גניא (ginnāyā) or Classical Syriac ܓܢܝܐ (genyā), also meaning \"a tutelary deity\" or \"Astaroth idols\". Compare Latin genius.\n\nDenominal verb from جِنّ (jinn, “jinn; spirit, demon”), leveled to the root ج ن ن (j n n)."},"ipa":null}